SIMPLE: wainscot
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wainscot
<hw>Wain"scot</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OD.
<ets>waeghe-schot</ets>, D. <ets>wagen-schot</ets>, a clapboard, fr. OD.
<ets>waeg</ets>, <ets>weeg</ets>, a wall (akin to AS. <ets>wah</ets>;
cf. Icel. <ets>veggr</ets>) + <ets>schot</ets> a covering of boards
(akin to E. <ets>shot</ets>, <ets>shoot</ets>).]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Oaken timber or boarding.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A wedge <qex>wainscot</qex> is fittest and most proper for
cleaving of an oaken tree.</q> <rj><qau>Urquhart.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Inclosed in a chest of <qex>wainscot</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Dart.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Arch.)</fld> <def>A wooden lining or boarding of
the walls of apartments, usually made in panels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any one of numerous species of
European moths of the family <fam>Leucanidae</fam>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ They are reddish or yellowish, streaked or lined with
black and white. Their larvae feed on grasses and sedges.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wainscot</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wainscot
<hw>Wain"scot</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Wainscoted</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wainscoting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To line with boards or
panelwork, or as if with panelwork; <as>as, to <ex>wainscot</ex> a
hall</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Music soundeth better in chambers <qex>wainscoted</qex> than
hanged.</q> <rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The other is <qex>wainscoted</qex> with looking-glass.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wainscoting</ent>⟦br⟧
